tle time for discussions of reflexivity, it remains a key topic in narratology, as does fictionality. The latter is commonly defined opposition to the real and the factual, but remains conditioned by historical, cultural, discursive, and medium-related factors. Reflexivity blurs the boundaries between fact and fiction, however, by giving fiction a factual edge or by questioning the limits of factuality in non-fictional discourses. Fictionality, factuality, and reflexivity thus constitute a complex triangle of concepts, yet they are rarely considered together. This volume fills this gap by exploring the intricacies of their interactions and interdependence in philosophy, literature, film, and digital media, providing insights into a broad range of their manifestations from the ancient times to today, from East Asia through Europe to the Americas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aFictionality.  afactual narratives.  ametafiction.  areflexivity.1 aCassou-Noguès, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChinita, Fátima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinkler, Michal Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolde, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFülöp, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFülöp, Erika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoffmann, Lukas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusnierz, Mathias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavocat, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLimoges, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r